  "prompt": "What are some cool Java tricks?",
  "response": "Certainly! Java is a robust and versatile programming language that allows developers to implement a wide range of techniques to improve efficiency, readability, and performance. Here are some cool Java tricks that you might find useful:\n\n1. **Use of Streams for Data Manipulation**:\n   - Java 8 introduced the Stream API, which allows you to process sequences of elements in a functional style. You can filter, map, reduce, and collect data in a very concise and readable way.\n   ```java\n   List<String> names = Arrays.asList(\"Alex\", \"Brian\", \"Charles\");\n   List<String> filteredNames = names.stream()\n                                     .filter(name -> name.startsWith(\"A\"))\n                                     .collect(Collectors.toList());\n   ```\n\n2. **Optional to Avoid Null Checks**:\n   - The `Optional` class helps avoid `null` checks and prevent `NullPointerExceptions`.\n   ```java\n   Optional<String> name = Optional.ofNullable(getName());\n   name.ifPresent(System.out::println);\n   ```\n\n3. **Method References**:\n   - Method references simplify the syntax of lambda expressions for methods that already exist.\n   ```java\n   List<String> names = Arrays.asList(\"Alex\", \"Brian\", \"Charles\");\n   names.forEach(System.out::println);\n   ```\n\n4. **Collection Factory Methods**:\n   - Java 9 introduced factory methods for collections, making it easier to create immutable lists, sets, and maps.\n   ```java\n   List<String> immutableList = List.of(\"one\", \"two\", \"three\");\n   Map<String, Integer> immutableMap = Map.of(\"A\", 1, \"B\", 2);\n   ```\n\n5. **Switch Expressions** (Java 12+):\n   - Enhanced switch statements improve readability and reduce boilerplate code.\n   ```java\n   int number = 2;\n   String result = switch(number) {\n       case 1 -> \"one\";\n       case 2 -> \"two\";\n       default -> \"unknown\";\n   };\n   ```\n\n6. **Text Blocks** (Java 13+):\n   - Text blocks simplify the inclusion of multi-line strings.\n   ```java\n   String json = \"\"\"\n                 {\n                     \"name\": \"Alice\",\n                     \"age\": 30\n                 }\n                 \"\"\";\n   ```\n\n7. **Pattern Matching for `instanceof`** (Java 16+):\n   - This feature reduces the need for explicit type casting.\n   ```java\n   Object obj = \"Hello, World!\";\n   if (obj instanceof String s) {\n       System.out.println(s.toUpperCase());\n   }\n   ```\n\n8. **Records** (Java 14+):\n   - Records simplify the creation of data-carrying classes by automatically generating `equals()`, `hashCode()`, `toString()`, and getters.\n   ```java\n   record Point(int x, int y) {}\n   Point point = new Point(3, 4);\n   ```\n\n9. **Sealed Classes** (Java 15+):\n   - Sealed classes allow control over which classes can extend a specific class, enhancing encapsulation.\n   ```java\n   sealed class Shape permits Circle, Square {}\n\n   final class Circle extends Shape {}\n   final class Square extends Shape {}\n   ```\n\n10. **Concurrency with the `CompletableFuture` API**:\n    - This API provides a way to write asynchronous programming in a cleaner manner than traditional threads.\n    ```java\n    CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> \"Hello\")\n                     .thenApplyAsync(result -> result + \" World\")\n                     .thenAccept(System.out::println);\n    ```\n\nThese features can enhance your Java programming experience by making code more expressive and easier to maintain. Make sure to adopt them according to your project requirements and Java version.",
